<title>SOUTH AFRICA: Investment gains boost Yabeng year profit.</title>
<headline>Investment gains boost Yabeng year profit.</headline>
<dateline>JOHANNESBURG 1997-06-12</dateline>
<text>
<p>Year ended Feb 28, 1997</p>
<p>			(million rand unless stated)</p>
<p>    Shr, (cts)		36.1	  vs 26.5</p>
<p>    Attrib income	   23.46	 vs 16.48</p>
<p>    Operating income	21.78	 vs 23.80</p>
<p>    Dividend income	 10.13	 vs 12.09</p>
<p>    Interest income	  4.67	 vs  2.33</p>
<p>    Net investment gain   37.77	 vs 11.88</p>
<p>    Depreciation	    10.83	 vs  7.20</p>
<p>    Financing costs	 26.95	 vs 17.31</p>
<p>    Pre-tax loss	     5.17	 vs  6.50 profit</p>
<p>    Tax credit		 1.08	 vs  2.76 charge</p>
<p>    Share of associates'   1.90	 vs  3.77</p>
<p>    Attrib to outside     25.65	 vs  8.95</p>
<p>    Turnover		 506.61	 vs 359.87</p>
<p>Full name: Yabeng Investment Holding Co Ltd</p>
<p>NOTE - Yabeng swapped its five percent equity holding in Sun International Holdings (South Africa) for shares in SISA, together with a small cash balance. It subsequently sold 7.73 million SISA shares for 25.5 million rand, generating a capital profit of 27.9 million. It also sold 194,000 shares in South African Breweries for 25.3 million rand, generating a profit of 9.6 million rand.</p>
<p>The company said it was its policy to declare a single dividend in May of each year.</p>
